# Qx Manual Test Suite

```elixir
Mix.install([
  {:qx, path: "."},
  {:kino, "~> 0.12"},
  {:vega_lite, "~> 0.1.11"},
  {:kino_vega_lite, "~> 0.1.11"}
])

alias Qx.{Qubit, Register}
pi = :math.pi()
```

## Introduction

This notebook is a **manual visual test suite** for the Qx quantum computing simulator. It is not an automated test — it is a human-facing confirmation tool.

**How to use this notebook:**

1. Open it in Livebook from the **project root directory** (so that `path: "."` resolves correctly).
2. Run each cell in order using **Ctrl+Enter** (or **Run All Cells** from the toolbar).
3. Each cell includes an `# Expected:` comment describing the correct output.
4. Compare the rendered output to the expectation. If they match, that feature is working correctly.

Each section covers a distinct area of Qx functionality:

- **Single-Qubit Gates** — Bloch sphere visualization per gate (Calc mode)
- **Two-Qubit Gates** — Probability histograms from statevector
- **Three-Qubit Gates** — CCX (Toffoli) and CSWAP (Fredkin)
- **Entanglement & Preset States** — Bell states, GHZ, preset helpers
- **Circuit Diagrams** — SVG circuit rendering via `Kino.HTML`
- **Measurement & Conditional Gates** — Shot-based simulation and `c_if`

---

## 1. Single-Qubit Gates

Each gate is applied to the |0⟩ state using Calc mode (`Qx.Qubit`). The resulting qubit state is rendered as a Bloch sphere. The dot on the sphere shows where the state vector points.

**Reading the Bloch sphere:** |0⟩ is the north pole, |1⟩ is the south pole, and equatorial states are superpositions. The +X axis corresponds to |+⟩ = (|0⟩+|1⟩)/√2, and the +Y axis to |i⟩ = (|0⟩+i|1⟩)/√2.

### H — Hadamard

Creates an equal superposition from a basis state. Rotates the Bloch vector from the north pole to the +X equator.

```elixir
# Expected: Dot at the +X equator (|+⟩ state, Bloch vector pointing right)
Qubit.new() |> Qubit.h() |> Qx.draw_bloch(title: "H|0⟩ → |+⟩", format: :svg) |> Kino.HTML.new()
```

### X — Pauli-X (bit flip)

Flips |0⟩ to |1⟩. Equivalent to a classical NOT gate. Rotates the Bloch vector from the north pole to the south pole.

```elixir
# Expected: Dot at the south pole (|1⟩ state)
Qubit.new() |> Qubit.x() |> Qx.draw_bloch(title: "X|0⟩ → |1⟩", format: :svg) |> Kino.HTML.new()
```

### Y — Pauli-Y

Applies both a bit flip and a phase flip. Like X, it maps |0⟩ to the south pole (with an imaginary phase factor i that is not visible on the Bloch sphere).

```elixir
# Expected: Dot at the south pole (i|1⟩ state; global phase i invisible on Bloch sphere)
Qubit.new() |> Qubit.y() |> Qx.draw_bloch(title: "Y|0⟩ → i|1⟩", format: :svg) |> Kino.HTML.new()
```

### Z — Pauli-Z (phase flip)

Leaves |0⟩ unchanged (it is an eigenstate of Z). Starting from |+⟩ makes the π phase shift visible: it rotates the equatorial vector from +X to −X.

```elixir
# Expected: Dot at the −X equator (|−⟩ state); |0⟩ is a Z eigenstate so it would stay at north pole
Qubit.plus() |> Qubit.z() |> Qx.draw_bloch(title: "Z|+⟩ → |−⟩", format: :svg) |> Kino.HTML.new()
```

### S — Phase (π/2)

Applies a π/2 phase shift to |1⟩. Starting from |+⟩, it rotates the equatorial vector 90° counter-clockwise from +X toward +Y.

```elixir
# Expected: Dot at the +Y equator (|i⟩ = (|0⟩ + i|1⟩)/√2)
Qubit.plus() |> Qubit.s() |> Qx.draw_bloch(title: "S|+⟩ → |i⟩", format: :svg) |> Kino.HTML.new()
```

### T — Phase (π/4)

Applies a π/4 phase shift to |1⟩. Starting from |+⟩, it rotates the equatorial vector 45° counter-clockwise, landing between +X and +Y.

```elixir
# Expected: Dot on the equator at 45° between +X and +Y axes
Qubit.plus() |> Qubit.t() |> Qx.draw_bloch(title: "T|+⟩ → equator at 45°", format: :svg) |> Kino.HTML.new()
```

### Rx(π/2) — X-axis rotation

Rotates the Bloch vector by π/2 around the X axis. From |0⟩ (north pole), this lands at the −Y equator.

```elixir
# Expected: Dot at the −Y equator (Bloch vector pointing into the page)
Qubit.new() |> Qubit.rx(pi / 2) |> Qx.draw_bloch(title: "Rx(π/2)|0⟩ → −Y equator", format: :svg) |> Kino.HTML.new()
```

### Ry(π/2) — Y-axis rotation

Rotates the Bloch vector by π/2 around the Y axis. From |0⟩, this produces the same +X equatorial state as H but with real amplitudes only.

```elixir
# Expected: Dot at the +X equator (same position as H|0⟩)
Qubit.new() |> Qubit.ry(pi / 2) |> Qx.draw_bloch(title: "Ry(π/2)|0⟩ → |+⟩", format: :svg) |> Kino.HTML.new()
```

### Rz(π/2) — Z-axis rotation

Rotates the Bloch vector by π/2 around the Z axis. Starting from |+⟩, this moves the equatorial dot 90° counter-clockwise from +X to +Y.

```elixir
# Expected: Dot at the +Y equator (|0⟩ would stay at north pole — start from |+⟩ to see the rotation)
Qubit.plus() |> Qubit.rz(pi / 2) |> Qx.draw_bloch(title: "Rz(π/2)|+⟩ → +Y equator", format: :svg) |> Kino.HTML.new()
```

### Phase(π/4) — Arbitrary phase

Applies an arbitrary phase e^{iφ} to the |1⟩ component. Starting from |+⟩ with φ=π/4, the equatorial dot rotates 22.5° counter-clockwise from +X.

```elixir
# Expected: Dot on the equator, rotated 22.5° counter-clockwise from +X (between +X and +Y)
Qubit.plus() |> Qubit.phase(pi / 4) |> Qx.draw_bloch(title: "Phase(π/4)|+⟩ → 22.5° from +X", format: :svg) |> Kino.HTML.new()
```

### U(π/2, 0, π) — General single-qubit unitary

The U gate is the most general single-qubit gate, parameterised by three Euler angles θ, φ, λ. U(θ, φ, λ) = Rz(φ) · Ry(θ) · Rz(λ). With θ=π/2, φ=0, λ=π this equals the Hadamard gate up to global phase.

```elixir
# Expected: Dot at the +X equator (same as H|0⟩, up to invisible global phase)
# U(θ,φ,λ) = Rz(φ)·Ry(θ)·Rz(λ); pipes apply right-to-left, so Rz(λ=π) first, then Ry(θ=π/2)
Qubit.new()
|> Qubit.rz(pi)
|> Qubit.ry(pi / 2)
|> Qx.draw_bloch(title: "U(π/2, 0, π)|0⟩ ≈ H|0⟩", format: :svg) |> Kino.HTML.new()
```

---

## 2. Two-Qubit Gates

Each gate is applied to a chosen 2-qubit input state. The resulting probability distribution is shown as a histogram. States are prepared without measurement so the full statevector is shown.

### CX — Controlled-NOT (CNOT)

The CX gate flips the target qubit when the control qubit is |1⟩. It is the fundamental two-qubit entangling gate.

**Qubit mapping:** qubit 0 = control, qubit 1 = target.

#### Classical input: |10⟩ → |11⟩

```elixir
# Expected: Only |11⟩ has P=1.0 — target (qubit 1) flipped because control (qubit 0) is |1⟩
Qx.create_circuit(2)
|> Qx.x(0)
|> Qx.cx(0, 1)
|> Qx.get_probabilities()
|> Qx.histogram(title: "CX: |10⟩ → |11⟩")
```

#### Bell state: H⊗I → CX → (|00⟩ + |11⟩)/√2

```elixir
# Expected: |00⟩ and |11⟩ each have P=0.5; |01⟩ and |10⟩ have P=0.0 (maximally entangled Bell state)
Qx.create_circuit(2)
|> Qx.h(0)
|> Qx.cx(0, 1)
|> Qx.get_probabilities()
|> Qx.histogram(title: "CX: Bell state Φ⁺ = (|00⟩ + |11⟩)/√2")
```

### CZ — Controlled-Z (controlled phase flip)

The CZ gate applies a −1 phase to the |11⟩ basis state. Phase changes are invisible in a plain histogram. An H-sandwich converts the phase difference into a visible amplitude: H⊗I → CZ → H⊗I maps |11⟩ → |10⟩ when the phase is present.

**Input:** X(q1) sets qubit 1 to |1⟩ (control active). H(q0) puts qubit 0 in superposition before and after CZ.

```elixir
# Expected: Only |10⟩ has P=1.0 — the H-sandwich converts the CZ phase flip into a bit flip on qubit 0
Qx.create_circuit(2)
|> Qx.x(1)
|> Qx.h(0)
|> Qx.cz(0, 1)
|> Qx.h(0)
|> Qx.get_probabilities()
|> Qx.histogram(title: "CZ (H-sandwich): phase flip revealed as |10⟩")
```

### SWAP

The SWAP gate exchanges the states of two qubits. Starting from |10⟩ (qubit 0 = |1⟩, qubit 1 = |0⟩), the result is |01⟩.

```elixir
# Expected: Only |01⟩ has P=1.0 — qubits 0 and 1 exchanged
Qx.create_circuit(2)
|> Qx.x(0)
|> Qx.swap(0, 1)
|> Qx.get_probabilities()
|> Qx.histogram(title: "SWAP: |10⟩ → |01⟩")
```

### iSWAP

The iSWAP gate exchanges two qubits and applies an imaginary phase factor i to the swapped amplitudes. Starting from |10⟩, the result is i|01⟩ — the probability distribution is identical to SWAP because global phase is unobservable.

```elixir
# Expected: Only |01⟩ has P=1.0 — same distribution as SWAP; the i phase factor is not visible in probabilities
Qx.create_circuit(2)
|> Qx.x(0)
|> Qx.iswap(0, 1)
|> Qx.get_probabilities()
|> Qx.histogram(title: "iSWAP: |10⟩ → i|01⟩ (i phase invisible)")
```

### CP(π/2) — Controlled phase

The CP gate applies a phase e^{iθ} to the |11⟩ component only. Wrapping it between Hadamard layers creates a two-qubit interference pattern that makes the phase visible as unequal probabilities.

**Circuit:** H⊗H → CP(π/2) → H⊗H

```elixir
# Expected: |00⟩ ≈ 0.625, |01⟩ ≈ 0.125, |10⟩ ≈ 0.125, |11⟩ ≈ 0.125
# (interference from the π/2 phase shifts probability away from |00⟩ toward the other states)
Qx.create_circuit(2)
|> Qx.h(0)
|> Qx.h(1)
|> Qx.cp(0, 1, pi / 2)
|> Qx.h(0)
|> Qx.h(1)
|> Qx.get_probabilities()
|> Qx.histogram(title: "CP(π/2): interference pattern")
```

---

## 3. Three-Qubit Gates

The Toffoli (CCX) and Fredkin (CSWAP) gates are demonstrated with inputs chosen to make the gate effect unambiguous.

### CCX — Toffoli (controlled-controlled-NOT)

The Toffoli gate flips the target qubit only when **both** control qubits are |1⟩. It is the quantum AND gate: with controls in |11⟩, the target is flipped; otherwise the state is unchanged.

**Qubit mapping:** qubit 0 = control 1, qubit 1 = control 2, qubit 2 = target.

#### Both controls active: |110⟩ → |111⟩

```elixir
# Expected: Only |111⟩ has P=1.0 — target qubit flipped because both controls are |1⟩
qc =
  Qx.create_circuit(3)
  |> Qx.x(0)
  |> Qx.x(1)
  |> Qx.ccx(0, 1, 2)

Qx.get_probabilities(qc) |> Qx.histogram(title: "CCX: |110⟩ → |111⟩ (both controls active)")
```

#### One control inactive: |100⟩ → unchanged

```elixir
# Expected: Only |100⟩ has P=1.0 — target unchanged because control 2 (qubit 1) is |0⟩
qc =
  Qx.create_circuit(3)
  |> Qx.x(0)
  |> Qx.ccx(0, 1, 2)

Qx.get_probabilities(qc) |> Qx.histogram(title: "CCX: |100⟩ unchanged (control 1 inactive)")
```

### CSWAP — Fredkin (controlled-SWAP)

The Fredkin gate swaps two target qubits only when the control qubit is |1⟩. It preserves the total number of |1⟩s among the target qubits, making it useful for quantum multiplexing.

**Qubit mapping:** qubit 0 = control, qubit 1 = target A, qubit 2 = target B.

#### Control active: |101⟩ → |110⟩

```elixir
# Expected: Only |110⟩ has P=1.0 — target qubits 1 and 2 swapped because control (qubit 0) is |1⟩
qc =
  Qx.create_circuit(3)
  |> Qx.x(0)
  |> Qx.x(2)
  |> Qx.cswap(0, 1, 2)

Qx.get_probabilities(qc) |> Qx.histogram(title: "CSWAP: |101⟩ → |110⟩ (control active, targets swapped)")
```

#### Control inactive: |001⟩ → unchanged

```elixir
# Expected: Only |001⟩ has P=1.0 — targets unchanged because control (qubit 0) is |0⟩
qc =
  Qx.create_circuit(3)
  |> Qx.x(2)
  |> Qx.cswap(0, 1, 2)

Qx.get_probabilities(qc) |> Qx.histogram(title: "CSWAP: |001⟩ unchanged (control inactive)")
```

---

## 4. Entanglement & Preset States

Bell states, the GHZ state, and the built-in preset state helpers are demonstrated. Entangled states show characteristic correlations in their measurement probability distributions.

### Bell States

The four Bell states are the maximally entangled two-qubit states. They are the quantum analogues of the four combinations of two classical bits. In each case, both qubits are in a superposition: measuring one qubit instantly determines the other.

**Bell basis:**
- **Φ+ (phi_plus)**: (|00⟩ + |11⟩)/√2 — both qubits correlated
- **Φ− (phi_minus)**: (|00⟩ − |11⟩)/√2 — both qubits correlated, relative phase
- **Ψ+ (psi_plus)**: (|01⟩ + |10⟩)/√2 — both qubits anti-correlated
- **Ψ− (psi_minus)**: (|01⟩ − |10⟩)/√2 — both qubits anti-correlated, relative phase

**Qubit ordering:** qubit 0 is the most-significant bit. |01⟩ means qubit 0 = |0⟩, qubit 1 = |1⟩.

#### Φ+ (phi_plus): (|00⟩ + |11⟩)/√2

```elixir
# Expected: |00⟩ and |11⟩ each have P=0.5; |01⟩ and |10⟩ have P=0.0
Qx.create_circuit(2)
|> Qx.h(0)
|> Qx.cx(0, 1)
|> Qx.get_probabilities()
|> Qx.histogram(title: "Bell Φ⁺: (|00⟩ + |11⟩)/√2")
```

#### Φ− (phi_minus): (|00⟩ − |11⟩)/√2

```elixir
# Expected: |00⟩ and |11⟩ each have P=0.5; |01⟩ and |10⟩ have P=0.0
# (same probabilities as Φ+; the minus sign is a relative phase, invisible in histogram)
Qx.create_circuit(2)
|> Qx.x(0)
|> Qx.h(0)
|> Qx.cx(0, 1)
|> Qx.get_probabilities()
|> Qx.histogram(title: "Bell Φ⁻: (|00⟩ − |11⟩)/√2")
```

#### Ψ+ (psi_plus): (|01⟩ + |10⟩)/√2

```elixir
# Expected: |01⟩ and |10⟩ each have P=0.5; |00⟩ and |11⟩ have P=0.0
Qx.create_circuit(2)
|> Qx.x(1)
|> Qx.h(0)
|> Qx.cx(0, 1)
|> Qx.get_probabilities()
|> Qx.histogram(title: "Bell Ψ⁺: (|01⟩ + |10⟩)/√2")
```

#### Ψ− (psi_minus): (|01⟩ − |10⟩)/√2

```elixir
# Expected: |01⟩ and |10⟩ each have P=0.5; |00⟩ and |11⟩ have P=0.0
# (same probabilities as Ψ+; the minus sign is a relative phase, invisible in histogram)
Qx.create_circuit(2)
|> Qx.x(0)
|> Qx.x(1)
|> Qx.h(0)
|> Qx.cx(0, 1)
|> Qx.get_probabilities()
|> Qx.histogram(title: "Bell Ψ⁻: (|01⟩ − |10⟩)/√2")
```

### GHZ State

The GHZ (Greenberger–Horne–Zeilinger) state is a three-qubit maximally entangled state: (|000⟩ + |111⟩)/√2. All three qubits are perfectly correlated — measuring any one instantly determines the other two.

```elixir
# Expected: |000⟩ and |111⟩ each have P=0.5; all other basis states have P=0.0
Qx.create_circuit(3)
|> Qx.h(0)
|> Qx.cx(0, 1)
|> Qx.cx(1, 2)
|> Qx.get_probabilities()
|> Qx.histogram(title: "GHZ: (|000⟩ + |111⟩)/√2")
```

### Preset State Helpers

`Qx.bell_state/1`, `Qx.ghz_state/0`, and `Qx.superposition/0` are convenience functions that return pre-built circuits. Here they are displayed as state tables using `Qx.draw_state/1`, which shows each basis state with its complex amplitude and probability.

#### Φ+ preset

```elixir
# Expected: table with |00⟩ amplitude ≈ 0.707+0i, |11⟩ amplitude ≈ 0.707+0i, all others zero
Qx.bell_state(:phi_plus)
|> Qx.get_state()
|> Qx.draw_state(hide_zeros: true)
```

#### Ψ− preset

```elixir
# Expected: table with |01⟩ amplitude ≈ 0.707+0i, |10⟩ amplitude ≈ −0.707+0i, all others zero
Qx.bell_state(:psi_minus)
|> Qx.get_state()
|> Qx.draw_state(hide_zeros: true)
```

#### GHZ preset

```elixir
# Expected: table with |000⟩ amplitude ≈ 0.707+0i, |111⟩ amplitude ≈ 0.707+0i, all others zero
Qx.ghz_state()
|> Qx.get_state()
|> Qx.draw_state(hide_zeros: true)
```

#### Single-qubit superposition preset

```elixir
# Expected: table with |0⟩ amplitude ≈ 0.707+0i, |1⟩ amplitude ≈ 0.707+0i
Qx.superposition()
|> Qx.get_state()
|> Qx.draw_state()
```

